Introduction

  1. hub_feature contains all numerical features by hubs from 2016 to 2019. Inactive hubs are denoted by 0 in status_at_Dec_19 column. This dataframe is used for cluster analysis (see the next section here)

Cluster analysis

Select six variables representing annual counts of programs, activities, participants and volunteers, hubs operation status, and years in operation for the cluster analysis.

Bring all selected variables to the same magnitude by scaling.

Determine the optimum number of clusters in the data using the elbow method.

fviz_nbclust(scale_data, kmeans, method = "wss") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 5, linetype = 2)

Alternatively, determine the optimum number of clusters in the data using the silhouette method.

fviz_nbclust(scale_data, kmeans, method = "silhouette")

Optimum number of clusters range from 3 to 5 clusters. Start by computing k-means with k = 5

set.seed(123)

km.res <- kmeans(scale_data, 5, nstart = 25)

print(km.res)

All large hubs from the previous section belong to clusters 4 and 5 whilst all small hubs belong to clusters 1, 2 and 3. The following table summarises the clusters

Clusters Hub counts Descriptions
1 1 Extinct inactive hub as of Dec 2019
2 15 Young bees small number of programs offered, average activity and participant counts, average hub age of about one year
3 45 Maturing hives significant program, activity and participant counts (but not many volunteers), havent been operating as long
4 14 A hive of activities lots of programs, activities, participants, volunteers and been operating for a long time!
5 1 Too many bees Large number of participants and 7000k+ volunteers in a year, this must be a data entry error
